</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1090,302,678]" pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Male: Body flattened, parallel, densely pubescent, dull. Head yellow, vertex with large black spot sometimes touching inner margin of eyes, postgenae black posteriorly, mandibles dark brown with black apices. Frontal tubercles usually yellow, in some specimens dark brown to black. Antennae yellow, apices of last five segments darkened. Pronotum yellow with three black spots (one median and two lateral). Scutellum black, elytra metallic green. Prosternum darkened, mesosternum yellow with large black median spot, mesoepisterna black, mesoepimera yellow. Metasternum black with paler posterior edge, metaepisterna yellow. Abdomen dark brown to black, last ventrite in some specimens yellow or with yellow posterior margin. Legs yellow, last two tarsomeres of all tarsi infuscate.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1090,302,678]" lastBlockId="16.[151,1127,223,1208]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="81" pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Labrum transverse, laterally covered with several pale setae, anterior margin shallowly but distinctly sinuate. Anterior part of head semiopaque, sparsely covered with long pale setae. Frontal tubercles small, subtriangular, covered with microsculpture, semiopaque. Vertex dull, with large feeble groove behind frontal tubercles, coarsely and densely punctate and covered with short pale hairs. Antennae filiform, 0.75-0.85 times as long as body, length ratio of antennomeres 1 to 11 equal to 18-8-16-22-20-19-19-18-17-15-19.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" startId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" targetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1089,1535,1581]" pageId="15" pageNumber="80">
Figs. 25-28. 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[225,376,1535,1554]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="snizeki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[225,376,1535,1554]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Apophylia snizeki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[385,453,1535,1554]" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1127,223,1208]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Pronotum tranverse, 1. 95-2.00 times as broad as long, widest at anterior third, narrowed posteriad, semiopaque, densely covered with coarse punctures and pale hairs. Surface with two large lateral depressions. Anterior margin widely and shallowly concave, posterior margin nearly straight, lateral margins slightly rounded. Anterior and posterior margins thinly bordered, lateral margins indistinctly so. Anterior angles widely rounded, posterior angles obtusely angulate and only indicated, all angles with distinct small tooth bearing one long pale seta.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1127,223,1208]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
Scutellum subtriangular with rounded apex, densely covered with small punctures and short pale hairs, semiopaque. Elytra parallel and dull. Humeral calli well developed. Elytral surface covered with small and very dense, confluent punctures and short pale hairs. Epipleura distinct but narrow, disappearing before apex. Macropterous. Metasternum bifurcate posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[244,324,703,727]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-184@15.[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 25-28. Apophylia snizeki sp. nov. 25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1127,223,1208]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Ventral surface lustrous, finely punctate and covered with pale hairs. Last visible ventrite with deep subtrapezoidal incision.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1127,223,1208]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
Hind tarsomere 1 1.15 times longer than following two tarsomeres combined. Tarsomeres 1 of middle and hind tarsi robust (
<figureCitation box="[513,592,831,855]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-184@15.[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 25-28. Apophylia snizeki sp. nov. 25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). Claws bifid.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1127,223,1208]" box="[182,524,863,887]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
Shape of aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[442,521,863,887]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-184@15.[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 25-28. Apophylia snizeki sp. nov. 25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1127,223,1208]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
Female: Abdomen yellow. Metasternum without large teeth. Last ventrite entire (
<figureCitation box="[1036,1115,895,919]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-184@15.[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 25-28. Apophylia snizeki sp. nov. 25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Tarsomeres 1 of middle and hind tarsi slender. Claws appendiculate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="81" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1127,223,1208]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,402,959,983]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Owing to the bifurcate male metasternum (
<figureCitation box="[880,961,959,983]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-184@15.[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 25-28. Apophylia snizeki sp. nov. 25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[983,1087,959,983]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="snizeki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[983,1087,959,983]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">A. snizeki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="16" pageNumber="81" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1871" box="[338,471,991,1015]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilitata">
<emphasis box="[338,471,991,1015]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">A. nobilitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Males of both species differ in the structure of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[159,232,1023,1047]" captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionTargetBox="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[246,276,1023,1047]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-184@15.[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 25-28. Apophylia snizeki sp. nov. 25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">25</figureCitation>
). Females of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[420,522,1023,1047]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="snizeki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[420,522,1023,1047]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">A. snizeki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[529,612,1024,1047]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
have the last ventrite entire (
<figureCitation box="[922,1002,1023,1047]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-184@15.[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 25-28. Apophylia snizeki sp. nov. 25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
), while it is incised in females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1871" box="[379,511,1055,1079]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilitata">
<emphasis box="[379,511,1055,1079]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">A. nobilitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[526,605,1055,1079]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-184@15.[129,1074,718,1502]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 25-28. Apophylia snizeki sp. nov. 25 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 26 – last ventrite of female; 27 – male metasternum; 28 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 25-26, 28); 2 mm (Fig. 27)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174154/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
